INSERT INTO `columnists_articles` (`id`, `columnists_id`, `title`, `description`, `article_date`, `thumbnail_image`, `data`, `is_active`) VALUES
(36, 30, 'Be honest: You didn’t see that coming, did you?', '<p>If at first you don&rsquo;t succeed, give up&rsquo; is a motto, that has served me well through nearly 48 years of earthly existence. So it is perhaps just as well I am not the trainer of Prince Bishop, because plainly he would not have won the world&rsquo;s richest race on Saturday. Fortunately, Saeed bin Suroor has the Godolphin gig and Prince Bishop duly ran on the Meydan card for the fifth successive year. Consider his previous efforts and it was quite an achievement: 2011 tenth of 14 behind Victoire Pisa in Dubai World Cup; 2012 seventh of 13 to Monterosso in Dubai World Cup; 2013 tenth of 11 to St Nicholas Abbey in Sheema Classic; 2014 ninth of 16 to African Story in Dubai World Cup. All in all clearly the ideal antecedents to: 2015 wins Dubai World Cup.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Of course horses can improve, but you could not see this one coming a mile away from a veteran Group Two performer. You might be tempted to suggest he has finally discovered his metier late in life running on dirt, were it not for the fact he plainly hates the kickback and had already been beaten twice at Meydan during the Dubai Carnival. Throw in the fact Prince Bishop&rsquo;s victory came after an extraordinary performance - he drops out of the TV screen with William Buick hard at work as they pass the post first time, then produces a startling mid race split and has the thing sewn up halfway up the straight - and it really was a truly astonishing result. Maybe the others simply didn&rsquo;t stay, apart from those who didn&rsquo;t like the track.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, despite the typically rapturous reception from an adulatory crowd after another hometown verdict, this result was possibly not quite as welcome as it might have been. Even Sheikh Mohammed himself seemed slightly bemused, describing it as a &lsquo;pleasant surprise&rsquo; but one can imagine the Sheikh&rsquo;s bloodstock advisor, Darley racing adviser John Ferguson has often eyed a big prize in March with the 8yo gelding. Unfortunately for him, it was the Supreme Novices&rsquo; Hurdle at the Cheltenham Festival he was thinking about. Even William Buick initially seemed as stunned as everyone else an old monkey like Prince Bishop had won the lion&rsquo;s share of the $10 million. Before regaining his celebratory mojo and waving the golden whip above his head (maybe he&rsquo;d just worked out his percentage), the jockey said he felt numb at such a surreal scenario.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was an important victory for Buick, whose Carnival hadn&rsquo;t been anywhere near as successful as his Godolphin sidekick James Doyle. African Story, the latest in a slew of unexpected results, signalled the death knell for the old Tapeta all-weather surface in 2014, when it was ripped out in a bid to entice the Americans back en masse with a return to their favoured dirt. Yet, while Tapeta produced a string of largely lacklustre World Cup winners, the return of the dirt has now come up with one of the biggest shocks you are ever likely to see. Okay, he was only 14-1 but frankly that looked a touch ungenerous and was only a function of how untrustworthy the new surface had seemed. Which is where we return to the Tapeta debate. My friend Michael Dickinson can hardly be regarded as an impartial observer given he created the synthetic surface, and more than once he has taken issue with things I have written on the subject.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Indeed, when I opened my e-mail folder at Meydan on Saturday morning ready to start my World Cup blog, &lsquo;Tricky Dicky&rsquo; had already popped one across. &lsquo;Tapeta unpredictable?&rsquo; it was headed. &lsquo;This week I read in the Racing Post (RP) all seven favourites won at Wolverhampton. Do you read the RP?&rsquo; Make no mistake, Tapeta is a fine surface &ndash; they have another nice contract now at Woodbine in Toronto, so Canada&rsquo;s senior Classic, the Queen&rsquo;s Plate, will be run on it from 2016. But my stance has always been it makes little sense to run such a senior race, one labelled the World Cup, on an artificial surface when virtually no other major race takes place on the same. You can&rsquo;t play the early rounds of the FA Cup on turf and then ask everyone to play the final on a plastic pitch. So in comes the dirt, and home comes Prince Bishop for the biggest shock since, er, Monterosso? Half an hour after the race, I had more mail from Mr Dickinson, pointing out a delicious irony.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lsquo;Prince Bishop trains exclusively on Tapeta,&rsquo; it read, and he&rsquo;s right, because Godolphin&rsquo;s Al Quoz gallops are indeed Tapeta. Elsewhere there were fine performances worthy of the stage all day long: Tamarkuz, Brown Panther, Mubtaahij, Sole Power - each one was memorable in their own way. Solow looked a new star in the Dubai Turf, though in hindsight The Grey Gatsby&rsquo;s entire display is a puzzle; he just did not look in love with the whole idea, but he still collects $1.2m for second, which is nothing to be sniffed at. Then there was Dolniya winning a Sheema Classic of the highest quality. If the total eclipse of the rising sun, notably via the lifeless Harp Star from Japan, could not be foreseen, there were still another couple of brilliant displays to come after the World Cup with the fireworks and Kylie (though personally I&rsquo;m more of a Taylor Swift fan).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But without meaning any disrespect to anyone involved with the horse, Prince Bishop does not offer much assistance to the World Cup in terms of credibility and prestige. He also beat the Americans, which also wasn&rsquo;t in the script, though California Chrome&rsquo;s part-owner Steve Coburn appears to have cleaned up his act since he lowered the tone with a churlish outburst after the Belmont Stakes. &ldquo;Sheikh Mohammed invited us to come over because he loves and believes in our horse,&rdquo; he said on Saturday. &ldquo;To run second behind one of his is a pretty good day.&rdquo; If he was &lsquo;starstruck&rsquo; by the Sheikh, I can&rsquo;t wait to see what he&rsquo;s like with the Queen when he comes to Royal Ascot! It cannot be far from accurate to suggest many of those close to the World Cup did not merely think the Americans would win, they actively wanted them to win; their coveted presence, after all, was one of the principal factors in removing the Tapeta. Enough of them ran well enough to suggest they&rsquo;ll be back for more.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Victory for the Bob Baffert-trained Secret Circle in the Golden Shaheen represented a return to normalcy that would have done Warren Harding proud, while California Chrome, Lea and Candy Boy (formerly American, making UAE debut) filled second, third and fourth. Ardent &lsquo;Chromies&rsquo; won&rsquo;t have been pleased to see him race four wide, though he still looked like winning until Prince Bishop parachuted in two furlongs out. Japan&rsquo;s top dirt horse Hokko Tarumae was fifth after giving a bold show, fading as he should after going too fast, and the non-dirt horses ran like nondirt horses. Thinking about it, the Dubai World Cup result starts to look more and more plausible. But only if you remove the winner.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nicholas Godfrey,<br />\r\nRacing Post international editor</p>\r\n', '2015-04-02', '444', '', '1'),
(37, 31, 'Hello from Hollywood!', '<p>Yes it&rsquo;s the <strong>HH Sheikha Fatima bint Mubarak Darley Awards</strong> and it all takes place on Friday night at the Dolby Theatre in Los Angeles - home of the Oscars. It really is a glittering occasion and a real red carpet affair when the &lsquo;best of the best&rsquo; Purebred Arabians in America receive their awards. It might not grab as much attention as the Oscars but certainly from an American equine view, it is undoubtedly their big night of the year and the award winners - leading owner, trainer, jockey, breeder etc - come on stage to receive their &lsquo;gold&rsquo; trophies and make an acceptance speech.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From a personal point of view, it is quite something being on stage at such a prestigious venue hosting such a big awards ceremony, but Lara Sawaya, who organises the event, has a class team around her and the evening, which marks 28 years of the Darley Awards, looks set to be another winner. Then 24 hours later, it&rsquo;s time for the prize winners to relax and enjoy a sumptuous dinner at the Beverly Hills Hotel. Between the two events I am hoping to pop along to watch the Santa Anita Derby on Saturday afternoon and, who knows, I might see another California Chrome. He won the race last year and it set him on the road to stardom and, of course, second place in the 2015 Dubai World Cup. California Chrome is now on his way to Newmarket, where he will stay and train for Royal Ascot in June where he is expected to run in the Prince Of Wales&rsquo;s Stakes on the opening day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What a great gesture by Prince Bishop&rsquo;s owner, HH Sheikh Hamdan bin Mohammed Al Maktoum, who gave his $6,000,000 prize money for the Dubai World Cup to the autism charity in Dubai. Not only is it a fantastic and generous donation to such a worthy charity, it also gives the charity plenty of publicity which can only do good. I thought William Buick&rsquo;s ride on the winner was one of the best rides I have ever seen from a jockey and to come from so far back, and beat the best in the world was some performance: and what can you say about the winning trainer Saeed bin Suroor? That&rsquo;s now seven wins in the world&rsquo;s richest race for the trainer - surely a Magnificent Seven! Buick, meanwhile, is now back in the UK and this Friday, he will be wearing the Godolphin blue silks at Lingfield where it is All-Weather Finals day with seven races and over &pound;1,000,000 in prize money.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tryster looks to be one of his main mounts as he goes for his fifth win in a row in the &pound;200,000 Easter Classic. Tryster heads a strong team from the Charlie Appleby stable that has sent out 68 winners on the allweather this season with a strike rate of over 30%. &ldquo;Tryster is one of the more exciting horses who will be running on Friday, along with Pretend and Portamento,&rdquo; said Appleby, who arrived back from Dubai on Sunday. Ryan Moore went straight to the airport after the Dubai World Cup and flew straight to Ireland where on Sunday, he teamed up with Aiden O&rsquo;Brien and rode a winner, The Warrior, at the Curragh. What makes this so interesting is Joseph O&rsquo;Brien was riding over hurdles that day because he is having problems keeping his weight down and it looks as if Moore will get &lsquo;more and more&rsquo; rides from the Irish Champion Trainer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After racing on Sunday, O&rsquo;Brien worked his big string out on the racecourse and it was interesting Moore rode John F Kennedy, the Derby favourite, Highland Reel, one of their 2000 Guineas hopes, and Together Forever who could go for the 1000 Guineas. Joseph O&rsquo;Brien meanwhile rode Gleneagles, the red hot favourite for the 2000 Guineas, Jamaica and Wedding Vow. Paul Hanagan is another man who didn&rsquo;t rest on his laurels and, after giving Tamarkuz a simply brilliant ride in the Godolphin Mile, was on the plane back to Doncaster where he rode two winners on Sunday. Mark Johnston certainly started the new Flat racing season in style and, on the opening day, sent out three runners all first time out in three 2yo races, and all three won. And fellow trainer Richard Fahey has also made a solid start and his Gabrial was a superb winner of the Lincoln Handicap, given a great ride by Tony Hamilton.</p>\r\n', '2015-04-02', '444', '', '1'),
(38, 32, 'Prince’s personal best sets poser for handicappers', '<p>There was a certain symmetry about the results on another compelling Dubai World Cup programme, as the visionary event celebrated its 20th anniversary: two winners for Sheikh Hamdan; two for France, and one apiece for Britain, Mike de Kock, Ireland, the US, and finally, most stunning of all, for Godolphin. But who would be an international handicapper charged with the task of unravelling some of the mysteries that unfolded and turning them into meaningful ratings? When Emirates Racing Authority senior handicapper Melvin Day set off earlier this week with the Meydan team responsible for staging the second Dubai Chengdu International Cup fixture in China on Friday, he carried with him a mass of seemingly imponderable questions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While Dane O&rsquo;Neill did a marvellous job of making all the running on Manark to give UAE stalwart Erwan Charpy a deserved first win in the Kahayla Classic, what might have happened had stablemate and previously superior Versac PY struggled and been virtually pulled up? Would Sloane Avenue, who ran an amazingly good race for Frankie Dettori from gate 15 of 16 in the Godolphin Mile, have beaten Tamarkuz, who as defeated trainer Jeremy Noseda pointed out was remarkably drawn one or two for the fourth time running, with a better stalls position, instead of succumbing by a short head? By exactly how much has Mubtaahij &ndash; only a modest fifth and seventh in Newmarket maiden races for Mike De Kock before he arrived in Meydan for the Carnival &ndash; improved relative to old rival Maftool, whom he beat eight lengths into second place in the UAE Derby?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How come Sole Power could not win the Al Quoz Sprint in four previous attempts, or even be competitive in three of them, yet at the age of eight he always looked as if was going to run down first Green Mask and then the final challenger Peniaphobia to justify following Tamarkuz and Brown Panther (Dubai Gold Cup) as top internationally rated winners of their respective races? Will the Dubai Turf runner-up The Grey Gatsby bounce back to his status as the highest-rated horse to appear on the programme after being backed into favouritism in the British betting market and tamely surrendering to his chief odds rival Solow?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What is it about the upbringing of the Aga Khan&rsquo;s fillies that transforms them into highly progressive 4yos, as Dolniya proved in the Sheema Classic by turning her short-neck victory over Flintshire in a Chantilly allweather prep race at the beginning of March into a two and a quarter length triumph over the Arc runner-up and Hong Kong Vase winner 25 days later? There are no easy answers, for the simple reason that at a well contested event such as this, where horses come from around the globe to compete at the highest level under track and timing conditions that are sometimes alien to normal training, some will perform to their best, while some will rise above or fall below their norms.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tamarkuz, the gallant Brown Panther, Sole Power and Golden Shaheen hero Secret Circle were winners who definitely ran to form. Manark surpassed his previous efforts, and although Star Empire and Havana Beat in the Dubai Gold Cup, Green Mask in the Al Quoz Sprint and Super Jockey in the Golden Shaheen were unsuccessful, it can be argued that they too achieved personal bests. Those who palpably failed to come up to the expected mark, for a variety of reasons including in some cases not handling the new Meydan dirt surface, are easily identified &ndash; Forjatt, Dark Emerald and Graphic in the Godolphin Mile; Dubday, possibly, in the Dubai Gold Cup; Sir Fever in the UAE Derby; Lucky Nine in the Golden Shaheen; The Grey Gatsby, as already mentioned, in the Dubai Turf; Main Sequence and Harp Star in the Sheema Classic, and African Story and Epiphaneia in the World Cup. And then, of course, there is Prince Bishop, the star of the pre- Kylie Minogue show, who came of age in the biggest race of all, when it mattered most, with Godolphin still waiting to strike. It seemed that at the age of eight &ndash; like Sole Power and one whole year older than Brown Panther &ndash; there was nothing new to learn about Prince Bishop, who has been under Sheikh Mohammed&rsquo;s stewardship since he bought for 80,000gns as a foal at Tattersalls in November 2007. He began his racing life with Andre Fabre and was unraced as a 2yo, being transferred to Godolphin&rsquo;s ownership as a 3yo after his first two wins in the French provinces, upon which he promptly beat Cirrus Des Aigles in a Group Two race. At the end of his first active season, in 2010, he was transferred to Saeed bin Suroor with an international rating of 118 and he has remained around that mark, give or take a few pounds, for four years since. In that time, in 20 races before Saturday, over a variety of distances from nine and a half to 12 and a half furlongs, and circuits ranging from Chester&rsquo;s tight turns to Kempton&rsquo;s Polytrack and Meydan of every type, he had been ridden by nine different jockeys, often occupying the role of the stable&rsquo;s second or third string, with three appearances in the World Cup resulting in tenth, seventh and ninth placings, and a tenth of 11 in the Sheema Classic. This year, when official ownership was switched to Sheikh Mohammed&rsquo;s son Sheikh Hamdan, the Crown Prince, but he remained with Bin Suroor, Prince Bishop&rsquo;s dislike of having dirt from the new Meydan surface thrown in his face was well documented, as was the way he battled on when pulled wide in the straight to finish a close second to his owner&rsquo;s Frankyfourfingers and his stable&rsquo;s African Story in his previous two starts. Come Saturday and his aversion to the kickback seemed even more pronounced, as his new regular rider William Buick forcefully cajoled him to stay in touch at the back of the field for the first half of the race. Perseverance paid off, and once in the straight Prince Bishop took on a new lease of life to beat the US pairing of California Chrome and Lea, with Doug Watson&rsquo;s American import Candy Boy an honourable fourth. The placing of proven dirt performers in Prince Bishop&rsquo;s distant wake suggests the winner has excelled himself with a lifetime best performance. Quite what that will amount to when the international handicappers produce their next set of official figures is the World Cup&rsquo;s biggest conundrum of all.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Howard Wright</p>\r\n', '2015-04-02', '444', '', '1'),
(39, 33, 'Mubtaahij indeed', '<p>Look out Louisville. Mike de Kock is going to the Kentucky Derby with Mubtaahij. The son of Dubawi made a mockery of the UAE Derby field, trouncing the lot by eight lengths in a time just outside the course mark established by Frankyfourfingers in Al Maktoum Challenge Round 2. Expect a bold show in the Churchill Downs feature in early May. Mubtaahij works on grass, without shoes, and has raced without Lasix his entire career. He is a winner of four races since December 31, when earning a maiden score. He&rsquo;s already run a Triple Crown. The son of Dubawi has significant stamina on his dam side, being out of Pennekamp mare, Pennegale. Whether or not Mubtaahij wins or runs a good placing, he&rsquo;s an ambassador for the global training operation that is Mike de Kock Racing, a competitive representative for the humble Sheikh Mohammed bin Khalifa Al Maktoum, and an ample canvas for Belgian showman Christophe Soumillon.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>De Kock does just about the opposite of every Americanbased trainer, and he&rsquo;s going to shake things up if Mubtaahij makes it to Kentucky in good health. The Kentucky Derby is one of the toughest races in the world to win, but it doesn&rsquo;t mean a good crack at it isn&rsquo;t in the offing. The 2015 Dubai World Cup meeting was as much about the good old boys mixing with the progressive future of racing; Dolniya and Solow, incredibly unexposed on their form, took big steps forward with wins in the Dubai Sheema Classic and Dubai Turf, and shouted their presence in big ways for their respective divisions. Racing doesn&rsquo;t often provide clear cut demonstrations of the future in a one way gambit like we saw from both. With the future of the pair still far ahead of them, their prospects for the remainder of the season seem incredibly exciting. Prince Bishop and Sole Power amply represented the pensioners, providing two wins for 8yos, and proving the antiquated adage, that if you try, try, try, try (and in the case of Sole Power&hellip;try) again, success is possible.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Previously, the two geldings made seven combined starts on World Cup night with Sole Power making the frame twice as the only placings. Do we give up too soon on some horses? Perhaps. Just about anything is possible in this game, and seeing these geldings get their biggest career scores at this ripe age was heartening. How about Tamarkuz? The horse of the Carnival, reeling off four consecutive wins, topped by the Godolphin Mile, missed the break in the big race, back to his old ways. In reality, it probably helped him manage the win. The son of Speightstown settled out of the speed battle up front and had some reserve to last over Sloane Avenue, who travelled wide from his gate. Instead of mixing it up with Frankyfourfingers, Free Wheeling and the others at the head of affairs, Tamarkuz broke slowly and established a good position trailing the pace. As it transpired, the sketchy gate antics played into his favour. Another season has passed in the UAE and we were left with some great results on the world&rsquo;s richest night of racing. Cheers to the victors, best wishes to the vanquished, and I will see you back in the UAE next season.</p>\r\n', '2015-04-02', '444', '', '1'),
(40, 34, 'A New Chapter For Joseph O’brien?', '<p>The riding arrangements for Aidan O&rsquo;Brien&rsquo;s horses over the weekend seem to be a sign of things to come: Ryan Moore flew straight back to the British Isles after Dubai World Cup Night so that he could ride the Ballydoyle runners on Ireland&rsquo;s opening Flat turf card at the Curragh on Sunday, while Joseph O&rsquo;Brien made the short journey to Limerick to ride for his father in a hurdle race. It would be wrong to read too much into this. Joseph headed straight up to the Curragh after his ride at Limerick to partner some of his father&rsquo;s stars in the trainer&rsquo;s traditional post racing, pre-season session of public racecourse gallops; and he is likely to be race riding on the Flat as the summer develops once he has been able to get his weight back down to somewhere near the nine stone mark.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, common sense says a man of his dimensions cannot continue to make the weights on the Flat indefinitely, and it is likely that he is now, at the age of 21, heading into the evening of his Flat race riding career. Joseph O&rsquo;Brien&rsquo;s career to date has been remarkable. With an Irish jockeys&rsquo; championship and a host of Group and Grade One wins including two victories in the Derby under his belt, in five seasons he has achieved more than most jockeys achieve in a lifetime. Over and above his tally of triumphs, though, he has caused us to reassess the adage that &lsquo;good horses make good jockeys&rsquo;. Richard Pitman, stable jockey to Champion National Hunt Trainer Fred Winter in the early 1970s, made that phrase the title of his autobiography. This was, of course, being too modest, as Pitman was a very good jockey who had earned his position and success. Even so, there have been plenty of examples over the years of jockeys&rsquo; careers receiving boosts through nepotism.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the truth is that what good horses can do is to make their riders successful and to make them look good. The same applies to trainers and jockeys alike: good horses make you look better than you are, bad horses make you look worse than you are. Being successful and looking good, though, is very different from being good &ndash; and it should not be overlooked that Joseph O&rsquo;Brien, as his record on outside rides demonstrates at least as clearly as does his record on his father&rsquo;s charges, is a very good jockey &ndash; and the fact that he has also been successful, courtesy of riding good horses, is merely the icing on the cake. If and when Joseph O&rsquo;Brien has to call time on his days as a Flat jockey, it will be the end of a very successful chapter, but it need not be the end of the story: it could merely be the start of another chapter, as umpteen top class Flat riders have demonstrated in the past. Over the years many talented riders have enjoyed success in their chosen profession of Flat race riding before increasing weight forced them to switch codes. Joseph could be the next to do so, and there would be nothing sad about that - as presumably A P McCoy will be very happy to confirm.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>McCoy is merely one of a long line of successful jockeys who had to readjust their riding ambitions as they kept growing. Among the great National Hunt jockeys of yesteryear, Josh Gifford rode a Chester Cup winner before becoming Champion Jockey over jumps, Dave Dick rode a Lincoln winner before saluting the judge in both the Grand National and Cheltenham Gold Cup, and Frank Berry preceded his nine Irish National Hunt jockeys&rsquo; championships by riding Giolla Mear to victory in the Irish St Leger in 1968. Frank Berry&rsquo;s great rival Tommy Carberry did it the other way round, riding a Group One winner for Vincent O&rsquo;Brien (Fordham in the Joe McGrath Memorial Stakes, which is now known as the Irish Champion Stakes) after he had already taken both the Grand National and Cheltenham Gold Cup. In similar vein, Jonjo O&rsquo;Neill rode Alverton to win the Cheltenham Gold Cup five months before he rode Sea Pigeon to win the Ebor. Furthermore, if Joseph O&rsquo;Brien can keep his weight low enough to keeping riding the top weights on the Flat as well as riding over jumps, he will merely be continuing a magnificent Irish tradition of dual purpose jockeyship, typified by Martin Molony who was Ireland&rsquo;s Champion Jumps Jockey in the post war years while also arguably the country&rsquo;s most respected Flat jockey.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In fact, in Ireland the convention of leading jockeys riding under both codes concurrently (which still exists to this day) was only marginalised by chance. In the early years of his training career, Vincent O&rsquo;Brien concentrated almost exclusively on National Hunt racing, in which sphere he was dominant. During the 1950s, T P Burns - who rode nine Cheltenham Festival winners between 1954 and &rsquo;59, and six Irish Classic winners between 1957 and &rsquo;72 - was the principal jockey for both his Flat horses and his hurdlers. In 1957 Burns rode Ballymoss to win the Irish Derby for O&rsquo;Brien, and also partnered the colt in England to finish second in the Derby and then win the St. Leger. He also rode the stable&rsquo;s promising filly Gladness. Things were going well early the following year when he rode two winners for O&rsquo;Brien at Cheltenham in March &ndash; but then he was badly injured in a hurdle race fall at Clonmel in May. Burns was confined to hospital throughout June, so O&rsquo;Brien needed new jockeys for Ballymoss in the Coronation Cup and Gladness in the Ascot Gold Cup. Scobie Breasley was booked for the former and Lester Piggott for the latter. Both horses won, and the new partnerships understandably remained intact throughout the rest of the season, during which Gladness took the Goodwood Cup and the Ebor, and Ballymoss won the Eclipse, the King George and Queen Elizabeth Stakes and the Prix de l&rsquo;Arc de Triomphe. But for T P Burns&rsquo; fall at Clonmel, the rich tradition of dual purpose jockeys might not have faded away as it did. The good news is that Joseph O&rsquo;Brien might be able to revive it.</p>\r\n', '2015-04-02', '444', '', '1'),
(41, 35, 'Prince Crowned King', '<p>The 20th edition of the richest race of all, the $10million Dubai World Cup, saw a return to its traditional dirt surface and welcomed the US Horse of the Year California Chrome, not to mention last year&rsquo;s hero African Story, Japan&rsquo;s Dirt Champion Hokko Tarumae and his compatriot, the second highest rated horse on the planet last year, Epiphaneia. Yet, as California Chrome delivered his challenge to Hokko Tarumae approaching the final 300m, both were engulfed by the mighty presence of the gallant veteran Prince Bishop, who hastily bade them farewell with the point of a toe. Successful in last year&rsquo;s Group 1 Al Maktoum Challenge Round Three, the chestnut 8yo thus completed a magnificent double for his sire, Darley&rsquo;s Irish 2000 Guineas, National Stakes and Prix Jacques le Marois hero Dubawi.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Three hours earlier, Dubawi&rsquo;s athletic son Mubtaahij had turned the Group 2 UAE Derby into an eight length stroll to become his 57th Graded and Group winner, 17 of whom have triumphed at the highest level. Prince Bishop&rsquo;s dam, North East Bay, is by the Group 2 A Phenomenon Stakes victor Prospect Bay, whose halfbrother Caller One was a brilliant winner of the Group 1 Dubai Golden Shaheen in both 2001 and 2002. By the fine miler Sure Blade, North East Bay&rsquo;s dam Wassifa is a Listed-placed granddaughter of Habitat&rsquo;s Sun Chariot Stakes heroine Topsy, a half-sister to the 1983 Derby hero Teenoso who produced a Derby runner-up herself in Most Welcome. After Sole Power had challenged Slade Power&rsquo;s mantle as Europe&rsquo;s best sprinter by adding the Group 1 Al Quoz Sprint to his dual victories in both the Group 1 King&rsquo;s Stand Stakes and Group 1 Nunthorpe Stakes, the US raider Secret Circle advertised his claims as the world&rsquo;s best sprinter on dirt by defeating the Hong Kong duo Super Jockey and Rich Tapestry in the Group 1 Dubai Golden Shaheen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Successful in the 2013 Grade 1 Breeders&rsquo; Cup Sprint and a close second in last year&rsquo;s edition, the bay is by Unbridled&rsquo;s Grade 1 Pimlico Special ace Eddington out of a Stakes winning three-parts sister to the Kentucky Oaks third Really Polish. This family is no stranger to success in Dubai, Secret Circle&rsquo;s fourth dam R Thomasina being a three-parts sister to Autocratic, the third dam of the 1999 World Cup hero Almutawakel, and to Hurry Call, the fourth dam of the 2013 Sheema Classic ace St Nicholas Abbey. Indeed, R Thomasina is also a three-parts sister to the 1955 Kentucky Oaks runner-up Lea Lane, third dam of the fine sire Miswaki. Famed as the sire of the Prix de l&rsquo;Arc de Triomphe heroine and wonder mare Urban Sea, Miswaki produced another magnificent broodmare in the Listed scorer Daltawa, dam of the best horse in the world in 1999, Daylami, and the best 3yo in Europe in 2003, Dalakhani.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By Azamour, Daltawa&rsquo;s granddaughter Dolniya swept to victory in the Group 1 Dubai Sheema Classic, her nearest pursuer being her compatriot Flintshire, whom she had narrowly defeated in a conditions event at Chantilly three weeks before. Indeed, her victory completed a fine double for France, Solow having sauntered home in the style of a future champion in the Group 1 Dubai Turf, reminding all of the wonder and grace of his sire Singspiel, Sheikh Mohammed&rsquo;s star who conquered the valiant Brazilians Siphon and Sandpit in that memorable epic Dubai World Cup of 1997.</p>\r\n', '2015-04-02', '444', '', '1'),
(42, 34, 'Achievement is not merely a new trend', '<p>IT is fitting that two of the supporting races on Rosehill&rsquo;s Golden Slipper card last Saturday honoured influential figures from the early days of the race. The George Ryder Stakes is named after the former Sydney Turf Club chairman who devised the &lsquo;Slipper&rsquo; and then inaugurated it in 1957; while the Star Kingdom Stakes commemorates the imported Baramul Stud-based stallion whose progeny dominated the early runnings of Australia&rsquo;s biggest juvenile race and whose descendants still do so to this day, notwithstanding that last Saturday&rsquo;s winner Vancouver is a rare example of a Slipper winner without Star Kingdom in his pedigree. We cannot mention Star Kingdom without thinking of Stanley Wootton, a member of what surely ranks as the greatest Australian racing family in history. Stanley Wootton not only bought Star Kingdom (who had raced in Britain as Star King) for stud duties in Australia, but also recruited the Colombo mare Oceana. He repeatedly sent Oceana to Star Kingdom, thus breeding not only the first Golden Slipper winner Todman, but also the 1959 MVRC Cox Plate winner Noholme as well as the successful stallions Faringdon and Shifnal and the good broodmares Star Ocean and Greatness. To describe the Woottons &ndash; which basically means Richard and his sons Frank and Stanley &ndash; as an Australian family is correct, based on the fact all three were born in New South Wales. However, as far as the full extent of their influence on racing went, they were citizens of the world; and for most of their professional lives, Epsom (in England, not Victoria) was their home. Richard Wootton was born in Taree (NSW) in 1867. It did not take him long to establish himself as one of New South Wales&rsquo; best trainers, and in 1902 he saddled Queen Of Sheba to land a gamble in one of Sydney&rsquo;s biggest races, the AJC Metropolitan Handicap at Randwick. However, the following year he relocated his family to South Africa. The reason for Richard Wootton&rsquo;s emigration was that his two eldest sons Frank (born in December 1893) and Stanley were blossoming as riders under his tuition, and he felt Frank was ready to begin his riding career. The only snag was they were still aged only nine and seven respectively, and the AJC stewards deemed them too young to be granted apprentices&rsquo; licences. Knowing the stewards in South Africa were less ageist, Wootton sailed across the Indian Ocean with his family. The upshot was that in October 1903 Frank Wootton, aged nine years and 10 months, set what is believed to be a record of becoming the youngest jockey ever to ride a winner of an official race, saluting the judge in the Germiston Handicap at Turffontein in Johannesburg. It is fair to assume this record will last forever! The move to South Africa was only intended to be a temporary one, with the family returning home when Frank was old enough (12) to qualify for an Australian licence. However, fate intervened: the minimum age for jockeys in Australia was raised to 14 as the result of a fatal fall in an apprentices&rsquo; race in Queensland. Frank was thus again deemed to be too young, so the family headed to Europe, settling in Epsom on the southern outskirts of London. The family&rsquo;s success in England was stunning. Richard Wootton arrived in Epsom an unknown, as his tally of three wins for 1906 suggests. Six years later his tally of 63 wins saw him the country&rsquo;s leading trainer by races won; the following year he was Champion Trainer, his 66 wins contributing to a haul of &pound;27,859. Frank Wootton&rsquo;s rise was equally meteoric. It was instantly obvious to the Epsom racing fraternity he was a fabulously talented rider, and in the 1906 season, aged 12, he rode 16 winners. In 1908, still aged only 14, he finished second in the jockeys&rsquo; championship. In 1909 he was Champion Jockey at the age of 15, his victories including the Oaks. He then retained his title in each of the next three seasons, his most successful campaign coming in 1911 when, aged 17, he rode 187 winners. Increasing weight, though, began to take its toll, and in 1914 he hung up his boots, aged 20. Stanley Wootton was also a successful race rider, his best win coming when Elizabetta won the Chester Cup under 6 stone 11lb in 1910 (with Frank riding the runner-up). However, his weight soon rose, and in 1912 he retired from riding to become assistant trainer to his father. He was poised to take over the stable when war broke out two years later.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Both brothers enlisted. They each served with distinction, with Stanley receiving the Military Cross for his courage in the Battle of the Somme in 1916. After the war, Stanley took over the stable and Richard returned to Australia. During subsequent seasons, Stanley was hugely successful, four times ending the year as Leading Trainer judged on number of wins. Frank resumed race riding, but over jumps rather than on the Flat. He excelled in this role too: his five seasons as a National Hunt jockey yielded nearly 200 winners. The notable success which Richard Wootton had enjoyed with apprentices was more than continued by Stanley. Graduates of the Wootton academy included Vic Smyth (a Classic winner as both jockey and trainer) and his brother Willie, whose son Gordon trained the 1966 Derby winner Charlottown; Derby winning jockeys Charlie Smirke and Joe Marshall; Champion National Hunt jockeys Billy Stott and &lsquo;Frenchie&rsquo; Nicholson; numerous other successful jockeys including Joe Caldwell, Jack Crouch, Bobby Dick, Dave Dick Snr, Pat Donoghue, Ken Gethin, Johnny Gilbert, Tommy Hawcroft, Mick Haynes, Staff Ingham, Alex Jack, Sean Magee, Pat O&rsquo;Leary, Dennis Savage, Jack Sirrett and Arthur Wragg. Zabara&rsquo;s 1000 Guineas victory in 1951 was particularly notable as both the winning trainer (Vic Smyth) and winning jockey (Ken Gethin) had been Wootton apprentices.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Several of the Wootton apprentices themselves went on to be great tutors. Frenchie Nicholson&rsquo;s proteges included Pat Eddery, Walter Swinburn, Paul Cook and Tony Murray, as well as his son David Nicholson. Dave Dick&rsquo;s apprentices included Dave Dick Jnr, who remains the only jockey to have ridden winners of both legs of the Spring Double (ie the Lincoln on the Flat and the Grand National over jumps). Staff Ingham&rsquo;s many excellent proteges included the outstanding jumps jockeys David Mould and Jimmy Uttley, as well as top apprentice (and subsequently very successful trainer) Brian Swift. Furthermore, Johnny Gilbert was the founding instructor of what is now the British Racing School.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Stanley Wootton&rsquo;s massive success as trainer of both horses and humans, though, ranks as merely a small part of his contribution to the sport. Despite the fact that he lived his entire adult life in England, his success as a breeder of horses in Australia justifies Les Carlyon&rsquo;s description of him in &lsquo;The Age&rsquo; in 1988 as &lsquo;arguably the most influential figure on the Australian turf this century&rsquo; and &lsquo;one of the immortals of the turf in Australia&rsquo;. Stanley Wootton&rsquo;s long term influence on British racing is equally profound: greater even than the legacy of the generations of horsemen whom he educated in Epsom was his gift to the Levy Board in 1968 of 206 acres of land on Epsom Downs (the arrangement is that the Levy Board took them on a 999 year lease at an annual rent of &lsquo;a peppercorn, if demanded&rsquo;) which prevented the demise of Epsom as a training centre, instead (one hopes) guaranteeing its existence as such forever.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And where does this trip down memory lane leave us? Well, it probably acts as a topical and useful reminder that, while the 21st century media like to portray the game&rsquo;s current major players as achievers at an unprecedentedly high level, high achievement is not a recent innovation.</p>\r\n', '2015-03-28', '444', '', '1'),
(43, 35, 'Guardian Angels At Rosehill', '<p>WORTH over A$3.5 million in prize monies, Rosehill Gardens&rsquo; Group 1 ATC Golden Slipper is the richest race on the planet for 2yos. This year, 16 lined up, but there was just one who mattered. Breaking with alacrity from his unfavoured outside stall, Vancouver was soon poised on the heels of the leaders, quickening smartly when asked by Tommy Berry to lead entering the final 100m before readily holding his stable companion English. Both first and second are trained by Gai Waterhouse, who thus enjoyed her sixth victory in the race, equalling the record of her father, the great TJ Smith. Indeed, just 40 minutes previously, Gai&rsquo;s charge Sweet Idea had swamped her field in the Group 1 ATC Galaxy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For Tommy Berry, it was his second Golden Slipper following success with Overreach two years ago. On that day, the first person to congratulate him was his twin brother Nathan. Tragically, Nathan died of acute epilepsy on 3rd April last year. This time round, an emotional Tommy was greeted in the winner&rsquo;s enclosure by his mother Julie, partner Sharnee and newborn son, a sleepily contented Kaidan Nathan: &ldquo;I have no words. Nathan is with me all the time. I have my son here, Kaidan. One person leaves you in the world and another one comes along. I&rsquo;m just so blessed to have my family here.&rdquo; Unbeaten in his four starts, Vancouver is by Darley&rsquo;s Grade 1 Travers Stakes, Grade 1 Whitney Handicap and Grade 1 Donn Handicap hero Medaglia D&rsquo;Oro and thus joined the likes of the exceptional Rachel Alexandra and last month&rsquo;s Gulfstream Park Turf Handicap ace Mshawish as his 13th Grade or Group One winner.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The tenth foal of his Listed placed dam Skates, Vancouver is the second to triumph at the highest level, following the victory of his Giant&rsquo;s Causeway half-sister Juste Momente in the 2008 SAJC Robert Sangster Stakes. By Danehill, Skates is out of At Talaq&rsquo;s fine daughter Skating, who won the Group 1 AJC Doncaster Handicap and Group 1 STC T.A.D. Kennedy Stakes in 1993. Sadly, Skating died earlier in the week, aged 25. &ldquo;At the 100m mark I called on Dean and at the 50 Dean persevered.&rdquo; Thus jockey Craig Williams urged his mount, the New Zealand raider Volkstok&rsquo;N&rsquo;Barrell to victory in the Group 1 ATC Rosehill Guineas after a rousing duel with November&rsquo;s Group 1 VRC Victoria Derby hero Preferment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For this would have been the 48th birthday and wedding anniversary of Dean Logan, handler Donna Logan&rsquo;s training partner and former husband who tragically lost his long battle with throat cancer earlier in the month. Runner-up to Mongolian Khan in February&rsquo;s Group 1 ARC New Zealand Derby, the strapping bay is by Montjeu&rsquo;s Group 1 HBRInc Mudgway Stakes and Group 1 WaikRC Waikato Sprint hero Tavistock. Earlier, another grandson of Sadler&rsquo;s Wells, Godolphin&rsquo;s Contributer had defeated the Japanese raider Tosen Stardom with a sparkling turn of speed in the Group 1 ATC Ranvet Stakes, thus adding to his victory in last month&rsquo;s Group 1 ATC Chipping Norton Stakes. Not to be denied, Japan claimed the fifth Group One event on the card, the ATC George Ryder Stakes, Deep Impact&rsquo;s 2011 Grade 1 Yasuda Kinen ace Real Impact prevailing in a dramatic head bob from Criterion after a thrilling final 200m.</p>\r\n', '2015-03-28', '444', '', '1');
INSERT INTO `columnists_articles` (`id`, `columnists_id`, `title`, `description`, `article_date`, `thumbnail_image`, `data`, `is_active`) VALUES
(44, 32, 'Ghazali and Bentley rewrite Qatar record books', '<p>While the northern hemisphere continues its march through the Classic season, Emirates&rsquo; racing teams have got their feet up, enjoying the summer break. Last week they were joined by their colleagues in Qatar, where Jassim Al Ghazali and Harry Bentley climaxed their recordbreaking achievements as the local Champion Trainer and Jockey respectively by sharing a treble on the final day of the 2014-15 Racing and Equestrian Club season at Al Rayyan Racecourse on Thursday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For Ghazali, who was winning his third title in the last four years, victories with Dark Leopard in the 1100m Thoroughbred maiden, Muhim in the 1400m handicap for Purebred Arabians and Roman Legend in the 1600m End of Season Cup for Thoroughbreds &ndash; following four winners the previous day &ndash; took his winning tally for the season to 176, which represents a significant advance on his 2013-14 record score of 140, which in turn beat a personal best of 99 in 2012-13. In contrast to most other major racing jurisdictions, Qatar&rsquo;s championships for trainers and jockeys are determined by an individual&rsquo;s prize money percentage total, and in this respect Ghazali&rsquo;s haul of 1.93 million riyals overtook his record tally of 1.66 million riyals in 2013-14.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ghazali further emphasised his domination of both Thoroughbred and Arabian racing in Doha by establishing a massive margin of superiority over the second most successful trainer, Julian Smart, who ended the season with 39 winners and a strike rate of 20.5 per cent from 190 runners, compared with Ghazali&rsquo;s total of 176 winners from an astonishing 1,355 runners, for a winning percentage of 13.0. Bentley&rsquo;s margin of victory over his nearest rival was equally comprehensive, as he continued his successful away-days from Dubai by repeating his 2013-14 jockeys&rsquo; title success as only the second rider to achieve back-toback championships since David Bouland&rsquo;s multiple successes ended in 2008-09. Bentley owed everything to the Ghazali stable, as all his 105 wins came from this source, and he further owed a new contract to his most recent exploits, which have led to his being signed by leading owner HH Sheikh Mohammed bin Khalifa Al Thani.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bentley&rsquo;s score obliterated the Qatar record for the number of winners in a season. The previous best was set by Bouland with 66 in 2007-08, when he also claimed a record of 808,000 riyals in prize money percentage earnings, which Bentley beat with a haul of 851,120 riyals. To complete the set of records, Bentley established a new mark for the margin of winners, as his advantage of 69 over Gerald Avranche, who took his score to 36 with a final-day success on Rasheeda in the 1400m Al Ghariya Cup for fillies and mares, totally eclipsed that of 29 between Bouland and Arnaud Bouleau in 2006-07. Roman Legend, who returned to a rapturous reception from the crowd, was a most appropriate winner of the season&rsquo;s final race, for he had blazed a trail from the start of the campaign, establishing himself as Qatar&rsquo;s first Thoroughbred Triple Crown winner in the Guineas, Derby Trial and Derby, all in the hands of Avranche.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The former British-trained 4yo found a subsequent step up in class just beyond him, although he continued to run with credit, and reunited with Bentley he won a handicap at the end of last month before signing off the season with a well-judged finishing effort that took him to the front 200m from the line and brought a one-length success for owner Mansoor Ibrahim Al Mahmood over the Avrancheridden Janoub Nibras. Roman Legend, who cost his original owners Paul Roy and his wife Susan 80,000gns as a yearling, was bought by Ghazali for 45,000gns at the Tattersalls sale in Newmarket as a mid-season 2yo, having raced twice, unsuccessfully in maiden company. His five wins from nine outings in Qatar earned a little over 1.28 million riyals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ghazali and Bentley were not the only record-breakers of 2014-15. In retaining the leading owner&rsquo;s title, HH Sheikh Mohammed bin Khalifa Al Thani comfortably surpassed his 2013- 14 prize money total of almost six million riyals and his earnings of 7.435 million riyals edged him narrowly past the previous record of 7.378 million riyals set by Umm Qarn in 2012-13. Splitting his string between the Ghazali yard and Julian Smart&rsquo;s Al Shahania stable, Sheikh Mohammed ended the season with 61 winners, the last coming with the promising Smart-trained 4yo Gazwan in the Al Musheireb Cup over 2000m on the final day. Marco Monteriso tracked the leaders into the straight and produced the British-bred colt on the outside to lead 200m from the finish, taking his career record to three wins from as many outings since the second week in February by half a length from the useful yardstick Vetlana De Faust, with the winner&rsquo;s stablemate Ghizwan running on to be beaten a further three lengths into third place. T</p>\r\n\r\n<p>he season&rsquo;s leading equine prize money earner was Al Shaqab Racing&rsquo;s 5yo Dubday, who improved on his second place to Assy in the list in 2013- 14 by extending his unbeaten sequence of races in Qatar with three top-class successes, in the HH Sheikh Mohammed bin Khalifa Al Thani Trophy, Qatar Gold Trophy and HH the Emir&rsquo;s Trophy. Stepping up in distance each time, Ghazali-trained Dubday looked to be in danger of losing his unblemished record more than once, but on each occasion he and Al Shaqab&rsquo;s senior jockey Frankie Dettori extricated themselves in the nick of time and class told in the end. The win that meant most to Dubday&rsquo;s owners was a repeat of his 2014 victory in the Emir&rsquo;s Trophy, where his strong closing effort took him to the front in the shadow of the winning post.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He gained the verdict by a neck from Ponfeigh, who finished the season in fifth spot in the prize money list but with the unenviable record of five second places from as many outings for owner Eng Hassan Ali Abdulmalik and trainer Debbie Mountain. Dubday&rsquo;s sole 2014-15 season defeat in the Al Shaqab colours came at the end of March, when he travelled to the UAE for the long-distance Dubai Gold Cup on World Cup night at Meydan, where he finished a creditable fifth to Brown Panther. Dubday is set to be campaigned in his native Europe over the summer. The vast majority of his Qatar-trained Thoroughbred compatriots will be taking things much more easily, readying themselves for the start of the new season in October. Qatar&rsquo;s top Purebred Arabian stars, several of whom will also be hitting the trail to Europe, were headed by Taraf, second in the prize money table for HH Sheikh Mohammed bin Khalifa Al Thani and trainer Julian Smart after three victories that included the HH Sheikh Abdulla bin Khalifa Al Thani Trophy and Qatar Gold Sword.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Taraf came up short when tried in the highest class, finishing fifth in Qatar&rsquo;s most valuable race of the year, the HH the Emir&rsquo;s Sword, behind Al Shaqab&rsquo;s outstanding, French-trained 5yo Al Mourtazez, who was making his debut in Qatar and of whom more is sure to be heard before racing returns to Doha.</p>\r\n', '2015-05-14', '444', '', '1'),
(45, 30, 'Triple Crown up for grabs', '<p>NO sooner had American Pharoah gone under the wire in the Kentucky Derby than thought turned to the prospect of his becoming North America&rsquo;s first Triple Crown winner since Affirmed in 1978. Actually, scratch that: people were thinking about it long before the Bob Baffert-trained colt entered the starting gate at Churchill Downs, such was the level of hype behind the son of Pioneerof The Nile, runner-up in the 2009 Derby for his Egyptianborn owner Ahmed Zayat. Now, at least there is a degree of substance behind the superlatives as American Pharoah heads out for the second leg in Saturday&rsquo;s Preakness Stakes at Pimlico, the historic racecourse known colloquially as &lsquo;Old Hilltop&rsquo; in an unlovely district of riot-hit Baltimore.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Frankly, though, he wasn&rsquo;t fantastically impressive at Churchill Downs as he took his career record to five out of six with a hard-fought one-length victory over the game Firing Line and his own Baffert-trained stablemate Dortmund. Even less impressive, though, was jockey Victor Espinoza&rsquo;s efforts in the saddle. Espinoza took the overland route, at least three wide on both turns. Admittedly, he had a wide draw, and the best that can be said is that he rode the horse with the utmost confidence. On the other hand, Espinoza has two ways of riding: at the front, or out wide. Not that it has hurt him in America&rsquo;s most celebrated race, which he has now won three times after War Emblem (2002) and California Chrome (2014).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Be that as it may, the least attractive part of Espinoza&rsquo;s ride came in the stretch, where he appeared to hit his mount on no fewer than 32 occasions. Think about it: 32 strikes of the whip. Okay, not all of them were proper bashes, but enough of them were, and quite how the horse was supposed to have time to respond was anybody&rsquo;s guess. American Pharoah moved off a straight line in the final strides as he mastered Firing Line and a more sympathetic Gary Stevens, who even seemed to stand up a bit in his irons as his rival moved over. Surprisingly, there was no stewards&rsquo; inquiry or objection: the cynic in me suggests the last thing American racing needed was the favourite getting chucked out on this number one showpiece occasion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Not that he should have been demoted, however, for American Pharoah certainly demonstrated that he was the best horse in the race, albeit under quite favourable circumstances in that the first three all the way round &ndash; Dortmund, Firing Line, American Pharoah &ndash; were able to set moderate even fractions. There was no &lsquo;cheap speed&rsquo; in the race, meaning the front was the best place to be &ndash; so the first three throughout were the first three home, in a slightly different order. Godolphin&rsquo;s Frosted, who finished fourth, deserves credit inasmuch as he had to close from off the pace. Now comes the Preakness, where the slight cut back in distance &ndash; this Classic is a halffurlong shorter than the previous one &ndash; is nothing like a worry for any of the Kentucky principals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They were all crawling home at Churchill Downs, with American Pharoah just crawling home a little bit less slowly. On a more positive note, he did win the Kentucky Derby, which is probably all that really matters in such a helter-skelter contest. Frosted is waiting for the Belmont, but the other five horses who comprised the first six are all expected back again. Given that American Pharoah is reappearing just a fortnight later, conventional wisdom might suggest such a hard race might leave its mark but my experience of the US Triple Crown tells me different. Time and again, Kentucky Derby winners come on for their run at Churchill Downs &ndash; after all, often it can be the first time they&rsquo;ve ever had a proper race, which is definitely the case here.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Preakness then becomes a lap of honour, often won much more easily against the very same group of rivals &ndash; think Funny Cide and Smarty Jones, for example. Since Derby fifth Danzig Moon is a stone closer, it is also hard to see his getting much nearer but Materiality could be a fly in the ointment. A spectacular Florida Derby on only the third start of his life, he totally missed the kick in Kentucky and had no chance whatsoever after that. Indeed, he performed miracles to get as close as sixth. With a fair wind and a clean break, he might be tougher in Baltimore. Then again, his trainer Todd Pletcher&rsquo;s Triple Crown record counsels caution. All in all then, American Pharoah is likely to add the Preakness to his laurels, after which all eyes will yet again be on Belmont Park on June 6. It&rsquo;s still quite a long way off. And, more signifcantly, that mileand- a-half at the &lsquo;Big Sandy&rsquo; is also a very long way home for most US horses, American Pharaoh included.</p>\r\n', '2015-05-14', '444', '', '0');

